Security Operations Fundamentals > [T3]: Avoiding Burnout: Tips for SOC Analysts

Analyst Fatigue and Burnout

Figure - zoom in

Landing a job as a SOC analyst is an outstanding achievement. You have a lot of hopes and plans and are excited to start investigating alerts immediately. That's nice, but you should be aware of things that kill your motivation and slow down your progress. A very concerning problem in Security Operation Centers is Burnout.

According to MentalHealthUK:

"Burnout is a state of physical and emotional exhaustion. It can occur when you experience long-term stress in your job or have worked in a physically or emotionally draining role for a long time." 

SOC burnout is the excessive stress you experience during work for many reasons. According to research carried out by Ponemon Institute, "Improving the Effectiveness of the Security Operations Center," 70% of SOC/IR analysts agree burnout is due to the high-pressure environment of their jobs. The leading causes of making working in a SOC/IR painful are:

  • Increasing workload: 75%
  • Lack of network & IT visibility: 72%
  • Being on call 24/7/365: 71%
  • Too many alerts to chase: 69%


Burnout is REAL! Treat it as a red flag if you ever feel chronic stress in your work environment. Additionally, 65% of SOC professionals have considered quitting their jobs due to stress. That may be the time to consider looking for another employer.

It's not normal to continually feel over-stressed at your job. Yes, there will be times with a lot of work to do, such as experiencing a breach or approaching project due dates, but this should not be the default situation.
 

Figure - zoom in

 

The solution

The good news is that there are options to reduce the possibility of experiencing burnout in your SOC. Still, unfortunately, most of them fall under the responsibility of SOC management. In other words, it's something you cannot control. Options to consider are:

  • Automation: automation is a force multiplier. Increases productivity with minimal resources. Automation = getting paid more for working less.
  • Removing distractions: your organization probably has hundreds if not thousands of connected devices and endpoints. Identify your valuable assets and prioritize where and how to utilize SOC resources.
  • Finetuning: a well-configured security device will significantly help SOC analysts. Think of how a well-configured and hardened firewall will stop attacks and alert for critical threats.
  • Hiring skilled analysts: as mentioned earlier, having one competent analyst is better than having 10 mediocre ones. An experienced engineer will save the entire SOC a lot of time and effort.


Addressing burnout requires a comprehensive approach based on people, processes, and technology. We admit that it's not an easy-to-solve problem but remember that employees are the organization's most valuable assets. As a SOC analyst, the most important thing to realize is to avoid making your early days' motivation drag you into the burnout trap. It's not normal to work 10 hours every day and be unable to find time to research and learn new skills. Work smart and not hard!
